Web Proxies

A proxy is a server that acts as an intermediary between a client requesting a resource and the server providing that resource. A web proxy is a server that acts as a bridge between clients requesting web resources and a web server. 
 

Figure - zoom in


A proxy server provides the following options:

  • Anonymization: when a client visits a website, the source IP address of the request will always be the IP address of the proxy server and not the client IP. This prevents leaking sensitive information such as internal IPs. 
  • Blocking harmful content: since all clients' web requests will have to go through the proxy, it's possible to use the proxy to enforce web access policies. 
  • Caching and performance: If a user requests a specific resource (e.g., browsing google.com), the proxy will save the requested resources (e.g., images present on the web page) and serve it to other clients requesting the same resource later. This way, if 10 users request the same website, the proxy will cache the response to the first request and serve it to the other 9 users.


A popular caching proxy server is Squid.

 

 

According to SLES Administration Guide:

"Squid is a widely-used caching proxy server for Linux and Unix platforms. This means that it stores requested Internet objects, such as data on a Web or FTP server, on a machine that is closer to the requesting workstation than the server. It can be set up in multiple hierarchies to ensure optimal response times and low bandwidth usage, even in modes that are transparent to end-users."

In most networks, a proxy is not a stand-alone server. Instead, it comes as a component of other security solutions, such as next-generation firewalls. 

Proxy logs are beneficial during security investigations because they can answer questions like who accessed what, when, and how. Proxies are also referred to as secure web gateways.
